</ul>

<p>You don‚Äôt need <strong>both</strong> Adrian and Stephane‚Äôs courses to pass the certification. One or the other should suffice. I used Adrian‚Äôs course as a primary study tool and Stephane‚Äôs as a supplement. Adrian‚Äôs courses have detailed projects that you develop throughout the course that provide real world type experience. Adrian‚Äôs courses have  more hours of content whereas Stephane‚Äôs are shorter and straight to the point for simply passing the certification. If I had to recommend only one, it would be Adrian‚Äôs for the projects since you get to do cool stuff like convert a monolithic web app into running on serverless architecture.</p>

<p>You will need Jon Bonso‚Äôs practice certifications regardless of whose course you purchase. The review mode on these exams are a complete game changer since Jon has very detailed explanations on why wrong answers are wrong and that had a lot of value for me.</p>

<h2 id="my-background">My background</h2>

<p>I‚Äôve been a life long learner when it comes to computers and have taught myself a good bit about programming, networking and server administration over the years but certainly not an expert in any of those areas. I did SEO and Wordpress development prior to 2014. Before switching into studying for cloud in 2020, I was studying to be a front-end web developer.</p>

<h2 id="my-process">My process</h2>

<p>If I thought it would take me 12 weeks to finish a course, I would schedule the exam for 14 weeks away. 12 and 14 weeks are arbitrary numbers just to make an example, not a guideline you should go by. You shouldn‚Äôt speed through these courses and should really try to internalize the content. If you fall behind and can‚Äôt make your exam date, PearsonVUE does give the ability to postpone the exam but you must do it more than 24 hours before the exam. This is roughly how I scheduled studying for my 3 certs:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Watched Adrian‚Äôs course from beginning to end. I took notes in OneNote because it syncs between phone and computer.</li>
  <li>Two weeks away from the exam, started Jon Bonso‚Äôs practice exams. There are usually 6 exams.</li>
  <li>Do review mode on the first exam. I use hand-written notes in this part because I feel it helps better with memory. Review mode is important.</li>
  <li>After first practice exam and review, I would spend a day using Stephane Mareek‚Äôs course to review areas I felt weak. His videos are short and straight to the point about certification content. If you only have Adrian‚Äôs course, then use his videos on something like 1.25x or 1.5x speed for review.</li>
  <li>Continue to alternate practice exams and going back to course content.</li>
</ul>

<p>There are several reasons I start the practice exams roughly 2 weeks away from the exam. One reason is Jon Bonso usually has 6 practice exams available. The time required to take the practice exam then review it will be well over 4 hours. That‚Äôs a lot for one day.</p>

<p>The other reason is the exams are very realistic and difficult which can be mentally taxing. If you don‚Äôt believe me, just search r/AWSCertifications for ‚Äúis jon bonso‚Äôs practice exam harder than the real thing?‚ÄĚ So for me, it just wasn‚Äôt a good idea to do these practice exams on back to back days. It felt better to put some time between the exams.</p>

<p>The practice exams will be hard, but don‚Äôt let it discourage you if you fail a few. I nearly quit because of it. I failed the first few practice exams for Solutions Architect and nearly cancelled the exam. Thankfully someone(<strong>thank you</strong>) talked me into going through with it. It‚Äôs not that Jon‚Äôs tests are so much harder than the real thing but they are a crucial part of the learning process. That‚Äôs an important thing to remember: <strong>the practice exams are a very important part of the learning process</strong>. That‚Äôs why I try to start taking them 2 weeks before the real exam and I alternate days something like this:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Monday: practice exam + review the exam - read explanations for EVERYTHING</li>
  <li>Tuesday: go over notes and review Adrian or Stephane‚Äôs courses.</li>
  <li>Wednesday: practice exam + review the exam</li>
  <li>Thursday: go over notes and review Adrian or Stephane‚Äôs courses.</li>
  <li>Friday: practice exam + review the exam</li>
  <li>Saturday: go over notes and review Adrian or Stephane‚Äôs courses.</li>
</ul>

<p>The practice exams are stressful but without them I wouldn‚Äôt have passed. Keep in mind this is all just my experience and I‚Äôm sure there are many who have successfully approached it another way.</p>

<p>Thanks for reading and good luck with your exam!</p>

